Beyond these three structural properties, a fractal rhythm also carries the _musical_ properties developed in the preceding sections. Its _interleaving_ may be homogeneous, as in the Fibonacci and Padovan cases, or clustered, as in the mirror; its _stability_ may be Pisot or non-Pisot, determining whether the rhythm self-corrects under perturbation; its _harmonic neighbourhood_ may lie within the Pythagorean region (the mirror's $sqrt(2)$ iterate) or outside it (Fibonacci's $phi.alt$, Padovan's $rho$). These properties are not part of the definition but distinguishing features of the particular fractal rhythm at hand, and they constitute the axes along which the triad $\{sqrt(2), phi.alt, rho\}$ of the preceding section is structurally organised.

It is worth situating this definition explicitly against two familiar objects. The Western metric system of nested note values — whole, half, quarter, eighth, and so on — satisfies the formal definition of a fractal rhythm in a _degenerate_ sense: it is the fixed point of the elementary substitution $L arrow.r L L, S arrow.r S S$, and its ratio is the trivial value $1$ (there is no inequality between letters). All Western notation is thus a fractal rhythm with rational ratio $1$, consistent at every level but harmonically impoverished in the sense examined in Section 4.5.3. The fractal rhythms constructed in the present sub-chapter are the _non-degenerate_ extensions of this structure: they preserve the self-similarity of the Western system while admitting inequality at each level, and the irrationality of their proportions is the price of this non-degeneracy.

Situated within the literature reviewed in @sec:state-of-research, the fractal rhythms of this sub-chapter contribute a specific refinement. The fractal tradition of Brothers, following Mandelbrot, has offered a broad analytical framework for recognising self-similarity in existing music; the compositional tradition of Nørgård and Johnson has introduced self-similar techniques for generating new music; the combinatorial tradition of Carey, Clampitt, Noll, and their successors has developed the mathematical theory of Sturmian words and their morphisms in the context of scale theory. What the present sub-chapter adds is the link between these three traditions and the phenomenon of rhythmic swing examined in Chapter 3. A fractal rhythm, on the definition given here, is not merely a self-similar rhythmic object — it is a _swung_ rhythmic object whose swing is consistent at every scale, with the irrational proportion that characterises its consistency emerging from a musical constraint (the preservation of swing under iteration) rather than being imposed as an external mathematical choice. The rules are not borrowed from combinatorics and applied to rhythm; they emerge from a musical requirement and only then reveal themselves to be combinatorial objects of independent interest.

With fractal rhythms defined, and with the triad of irrational proportions that organises their simplest cases identified, the final task of the present sub-chapter is to situate these objects within the topological perspective that governs the chapter as a whole. The notion of _neighbourhood_ from Section 3.2.1, the _potential energy_ of Section 3.1.3, the _Quplets_ of Section 4.4, and the fractal rhythms of the present sub-chapter are not four unrelated constructions but four views of a single topological structure on the space of rhythmic subdivisions. That structure, and its implications for a future topology of musical rhythm, is the subject of the next section.